: The {{ill|Ichijima Kawasu Matsuri|ja|市島川裾まつり|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} is a river festival held along the {{ill|Takeda River (Hyōgo and Kyoto)|ja|竹田川 (兵庫県・京都府)|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, a tributary of the {{ill|Yura River (Japan)|ja|由良川|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Taking place on July 29, it features floating lanterns and a fireworks display of around 750 shells. Other related festivals in Tanba City include the "Ganso Kawasu Matsuri" in {{ill|Hikami, Hyōgo|ja|氷上町|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, "Kita Goi Kawasu Matsuri," and "Naramatsu Kawasu Matsuri."

; {{ill|Shin'onsen, Hyōgo|ja|新温泉町|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Mikata District, Hyōgo|ja|美方郡|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
: The Kawashimo Grand Festival is a river festival held at the {{ill|Kishida River|ja|岸田川|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Kuto River|ja|久斗川|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Tai River|ja|田井川|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. As the annual festival of {{ill|Utono Shrine|ja|宇都野神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, it includes performances of the {{ill|Kirin Shishi-mai|ja|麒麟獅子舞|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, designated as an Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property of Hyōgo Prefecture. The festival features a procession of mikoshi (portable shrines) and a large fireworks display with around 3,000 shells, recognized as one of the {{ill|Three Great Festivals of Tajima|ja|但馬三大祭り|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

; {{ill|Amino, Kyōtango|ja|網野町|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Kyōtango, Kyoto|ja|京丹後市|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
: The {{ill|Asamogawa Minazuki Matsuri|ja|浅茂川水無月祭|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (commonly known as "Kawasso-san") is held annually on July 30 in Asamogawa, Amino, Kyōtango. The festival includes a sea-going mikoshi procession and concludes with a large summer fireworks display.

